## What to extract
You will extract TWO kinds of derived items:

### A) Atomic thoughts (meaning-bearing, project-relevant)
Extract ONLY if the statement has “charge” AND impacts a project.
Valid atom types:
- rule (governs future behavior/design)
- decision (I will / I won’t / finalized choice)
- intent (I want to / aim to)
- insight (changes understanding; affects approach)
- tension (feels wrong; resistance; anxiety; discomfort)
- pull (recurring attraction toward something)
- todo (specific next action)
- spec (requirement / design constraint / workflow definition)
- risk (danger, failure mode, fragility)

Atomic thought quality rules:
- Must be self-contained (no “it/this/that/he/she” without resolving what it refers to)
- Keep closest to original meaning; light cleanup is allowed, no reinterpretation
- Keep it short (1–5 lines). If longer, split into multiple atoms.

### B) Events (factual happenings / actions taken)
Extract events when the raw text states something happened, was done, was tried, was created, or a tool produced an outcome.
Examples:
- “Created repo …”
- “Enabled API …”
- “Bought app …”
- “Published thought …”
- “AssemblyAI errored …”
- “Deleted GCP bucket …”

Event quality rules:
- Factual, concrete, past-tense
- One event per file
- No moralizing, no philosophy in events

## What NOT to extract
- Pure narration/imagination/philosophy that does not change a project decision/design
- Repeated re-statements of the same idea in the same raw file (dedupe within the file)
- Vague “maybe someday” unless it creates a project-relevant intent/spec/decision

## Run instruction (what to do when user says “process”)
When the user asks to process raw thoughts:
1) Read `state/processed_raw.txt`
2) Find raw files under `raw/` not yet processed
3) For each new raw file:
   - Extract atoms + events per rules above
   - Write files to correct project folders
   - Rewrite relevant project summaries
   - Append raw file path to `state/processed_raw.txt`
4) Do not modify raw files

